Hi Jerin, I saw your nice RMSE matrix. So I tried out making a matrix of Recursive Cross Validation MSEs introduced in the textbook.


Choose the Best Model Based on Recursive Cross Validation MSEs

The First Difference of the Training Data Is Stationary

Assume we only have the 80% training data available when we forecast. The 80% training data don’t pass the ADF stationarity test. But their first difference does under the 5% critical value. The ACF and the PACF oscillating decay, suggesting an ARMA process.


Recursive Cross Validation MSEs



I wrote a function to carry out the recursive cross validation and output the table. The MSE comparison table shows the ARIMA(4,1,4) has the lowest MSE calculated from the Recursive Cross Validation method introduced in the textbook. So I’ll model and forecast the series with ARIMA(4,1,4)

Using ARIMA(4,1,4), the training set residuals pass the ADF test of stationarity with a p-value less than 0.01, but not the Box-Ljung test of independence.


Forecast Using ARIMA(4,1,4)

The model overestimates. The test set residuals’ ACF exponentially decays, while their PACF cuts off after lag 2, suggesting an AR(1) process. The test set residuals pass the ADF test of stationarity with a p-value less than 0.01, but not the Box-Ljung test of independence.
